Section 1:
132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST REGULAR SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 1163
H.P. 768 House of Representatives, March 20, 2025
by Creating an Additional Pathway to Certify Industrial Arts
Teachers
Reference to the Committee on Education and Cultural Affairs suggested and ordered
printed.
ROBERT B. HUNT
Clerk
Presented by Representative CARLOW of Buxton.
Cosponsored by Senator RAFFERTY of York and
Representatives: CROCKETT of Portland, DODGE of Belfast, LYMAN of Livermore Falls,
MURPHY of Scarborough, SARGENT of York, Senators: President DAUGHTRY of
Cumberland, LIBBY of Cumberland.
Printed on recycled paper
1 Be it enacted by the People of the State of Maine as follows:
2 Sec. 1. 20-A MRSA §13027 is enacted to read:
3 §13027. Teacher certificate with industrial arts endorsement
4 A person who meets the eligibility requirements of subsection 2 may apply for an
5 endorsement on a teacher certificate for a component of industrial arts with experiential,
6 laboratory-based instruction as described in subsection 1 by filing an application with the
7 department. The commissioner shall review the application, and if the commissioner
8 approves the application, the commissioner shall issue the endorsement.
9 1. Components. The components of industrial arts for which a teacher may obtain an
10 endorsement on a teacher certificate include, but are not limited to, automotive body repair,
11 diagnostics and mechanics, welding, electrical, carpentry and computer-aided design.
12 2. Eligibility. At a minimum, a teacher must meet the following qualifications in order
13 to be eligible for an endorsement:
14 A. Completion of an apprenticeship program registered with a statewide or national
15 apprenticeship and training organization;
16 B. Completion of a 2-year degree or certificate from a technical institution accredited
17 by a national association of career and technical schools or similar organization;
18 C. Completion of a minimum number of hours of paid applied employment or teaching
19 in the component area for which the endorsement is sought; and
20 D. Completion of a minimum number of hours of experience learning the trade or craft
21 in the component area for which the endorsement is sought.
22 3. Rules. The department shall adopt rules to implement this section. Rules adopted
23 pursuant to this subsection are major substantive rules as defined in Title 5, chapter 375,
24 subchapter 2-A.
25 SUMMARY
2266 This bill creates a pathway for a teacher to obtain an endorsement on a teacher
2277 certificate for a component of industrial arts with experiential, laboratory-based instruction.
2288 For a teacher to be eligible for an endorsement, the teacher must have: completed an
2299 apprenticeship program; completed a 2-year degree or certificate from a technical
3300 institution; completed a minimum number of hours of paid applied employment or teaching
3311 in the component area for which the endorsement is sought; and completed a minimum
3322 number of hours of experience learning the trade or craft for which the endorsement is
3333 sought.
